🧩 What Problem Are We Solving?
📌 The Core Problem

We are solving the problem of building a reliable, scalable, and secure digital banking system that can handle:

Many users at the same time

Financial transactions without data loss

System failures without downtime

Growth in traffic and features over time

In simple words:

How do we safely move money for millions of users, 24/7, without breaking the system?

❌ Problems With a Naive System

If we build a simple app:

One backend

One database

One deployment

We will face:

1️⃣ Scalability Problem

More users → system becomes slow

Can’t scale only the busy parts

2️⃣ Reliability Problem

One bug or crash → entire system down

No isolation between features

3️⃣ Consistency Problem

Partial failures cause:

Money debited but not credited

Duplicate transactions

4️⃣ Deployment Problem

Small change requires redeploying everything

Higher risk during releases

5️⃣ Team & Growth Problem

Hard for multiple teams to work in parallel

Code becomes tightly coupled

✅ What Our System Must Guarantee

For a banking system, some things are non-negotiable:

🔐 Security

Only authorized users access data

Every request is authenticated

💰 Data Integrity

No lost or duplicate transactions

Correct balances at all times

⚡ Performance

Fast balance checks

Quick responses even under load

🔄 Availability

System works even if one service fails

📈 Scalability

Can handle growth in users and transactions

🧠 Why Architecture Matters Here

The problem is not just writing APIs.

We must decide:

How services talk to each other

What happens when something fails

Which operations must be synchronous

Which can be asynchronous

How to scale safely

That’s why we need:

Microservices → isolation & scaling

Kafka → reliable async communication

API Gateway → centralized security & routing

Cache → performance

Kubernetes → availability & auto-scaling

🏦 Real-World Example

Imagine:

1,00,000 users transfer money at the same time

Notification service goes down

❓ Should money transfers fail?

Correct answer: NO ❌
Transfers must succeed, notifications can retry later.

👉 This is the core problem we’re solving:

Separate critical paths from non-critical ones.

