🧱 Monolith vs 🧩 Microservices
🎯 Goal of This Section

After this, you should be able to answer:

“Why did you choose this architecture?”

🧱 What Is a Monolith?
Definition

A monolithic application is:

One codebase

One deployment

Usually one database

All features packaged together

Example (Banking Monolith)
Banking App
 ├── User Management
 ├── Account Management
 ├── Transactions
 ├── Notifications
 └── Reporting


Everything runs as one unit.

✅ Advantages of Monolith

Simple to start

Easy debugging

Faster initial development

No network overhead

❌ Disadvantages of Monolith

Hard to scale specific features

One failure can affect everything

Large codebase becomes messy

Slow deployments

Difficult for large teams

🧩 What Are Microservices?
Definition

A microservices architecture:

Breaks application into small services

Each service has:

Its own codebase

Its own database

Its own deployment

Example (Banking Microservices)
Auth Service
User Service
Account Service
Transaction Service
Notification Service


Each service:

Runs independently

Communicates via REST or events

✅ Advantages of Microservices

Independent scaling

Fault isolation

Faster deployments

Better team ownership

Technology flexibility

❌ Disadvantages of Microservices

Complex infrastructure

Network latency

Distributed debugging

Data consistency challenges

Higher operational cost

🧠 The BIG MISUNDERSTANDING

❌ Wrong thinking

“Microservices are better than monoliths”

✅ Correct thinking

“Microservices solve scaling and organizational problems — not coding problems”

🏗️ Why We Start With a Monolith
Reason 1: Domain Understanding

Early stage = unclear boundaries

Monolith helps discover:

What belongs together

What changes together

Reason 2: Faster Learning

One codebase

Easier to debug

Faster feedback loop

Reason 3: Avoid Premature Complexity

Microservices need:

Gateway

Discovery

Security

Monitoring

CI/CD

👉 Doing this too early slows you down.

🔄 When to Split Into Microservices

We split only when:

Traffic increases

Teams grow

Certain modules scale independently

Deployment becomes painful

Example Split in Our Project
Monolith
 ├── Auth
 ├── User
 ├── Account
 ├── Transaction
 └── Notification


⬇️ Later becomes ⬇️

Auth Service
User Service
Account Service
Transaction Service
Notification Service

🔥 Interview-Ready Explanation (VERY IMPORTANT)

“We started with a monolith to understand the domain and avoid premature complexity. Once the system grew and we identified clear service boundaries, we gradually decomposed it into microservices for better scalability and fault isolation.”

