🧠 Core System Design Concepts (40 mins)

We’ll cover only what matters, with banking examples.

1️⃣ Scalability
What It Means

Ability of the system to handle increased load.

Types of Scaling
🔼 Vertical Scaling

Add more CPU/RAM to one machine

Simple but limited

❌ Not enough for large systems

➕ Horizontal Scaling (Preferred)

Add more instances

Use load balancer

Requires stateless services

✅ Used in microservices

Key Idea

Services must be stateless to scale horizontally.

Why?

Any request can go to any instance

No dependency on local memory

Banking Example

Balance check API

10 instances behind load balancer

Requests distributed evenly

2️⃣ Availability
What It Means

System remains accessible even during failures.

How Systems Fail

Service crash

Network issue

Database downtime

How We Achieve Availability

Multiple service instances

Health checks

Auto-restart

Load balancing

Banking Example

If 1 Transaction Service instance fails:

Traffic routed to healthy instances

Users don’t notice

3️⃣ Reliability
What It Means

System behaves correctly over time.

Common Failure Scenarios

Timeout

Partial failure

Downstream service slow

Solutions

Retry (carefully)

Circuit Breaker

Timeout configuration

Important Rule

Retrying everything blindly can make failures worse.

4️⃣ Consistency
What It Means

All users see correct and expected data.

ACID (Strong Consistency)

Used for:

Account balance

Transactions

Properties:

Atomic

Consistent

Isolated

Durable

BASE (Eventual Consistency)

Used for:

Notifications

Analytics

Reports

Banking Rule

Money movement must be strongly consistent
Notifications can be eventually consistent

5️⃣ Performance
What It Means

Fast response under load.

Techniques

Caching

Async processing

Database indexing

Banking Example

Balance read → cache

Notification → async

