🏗️ High-Level Architecture Components (30 mins)

The goal here is not coding — it’s understanding why each block exists.

🧭 1️⃣ API Gateway
What It Is

A single entry point for all client requests.

Client → API Gateway → Services

Why We Need It

Authentication & authorization

Routing requests

Rate limiting

Logging & monitoring

Banking Example

Client sends request with JWT

Gateway validates token

Only then forwards request

👉 Security is centralized

🔐 2️⃣ Authentication Service
Responsibility

User login

Token generation

Identity verification

Why Separate Service?

Security is critical

Reusable across services

Single source of truth

🧠 3️⃣ Business Microservices

These do the actual work.

Service	Responsibility
User Service	Profile, KYC
Account Service	Balance
Transaction Service	Money transfer
Notification Service	Email/SMS
Key Rule

Each service owns its own data.

🗄️ 4️⃣ Database (Per Service)
Why Separate DB?

Loose coupling

Independent scaling

Fault isolation

Example

Account DB

Transaction DB

❌ No shared tables

⚡ 5️⃣ Cache (Redis)
Why Cache?

Reduce DB load

Faster reads

What Goes in Cache?

Balance read

User profile

❌ Never cache critical writes

📬 6️⃣ Kafka (Async Messaging)
Why Kafka?

Decouple services

Handle spikes

Guaranteed delivery

Banking Example

Transaction success → event

Notification service consumes event

👉 Transaction doesn’t wait for notification

☸️ 7️⃣ Kubernetes
What Problem It Solves

Auto-scaling

Self-healing

Deployment

Banking Example

Traffic spike → auto-scale

Pod crash → auto-restart

🔄 8️⃣ Data Flow (End-to-End)
Money Transfer Flow
Client
 → Gateway
 → Transaction Service
 → Account Service
 → DB Commit
 → Kafka Event
 → Notification Service


Critical path: transfer
Non-critical: notification

🎤 Interview-Ready Summary

“The API Gateway handles cross-cutting concerns like security and routing. Core services are stateless and own their data. Critical operations are synchronous and strongly consistent, while non-critical workflows use Kafka for asynchronous processing. Kubernetes ensures scalability and availability.”

